              "@type": "Question",
              "name": "What is the difference between an SPV and a regular subsidiary in India?",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "Both are subsidiaries under Section 2(87) of the Companies Act, 2013 - the holding company holds more than 50 percent of share capital or controls Board composition. The legal difference lies in the MoA. A regular subsidiary has a wide main-object clause and can pursue any commercial activity within that clause. An SPV has a NARROW main-object clause restricted to a specific project, asset, or transaction. The narrow clause is what gives lenders comfort that SPV assets are ring-fenced and bankruptcy-remote from the parent and from other group entities."
              }
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "name": "Is a holding company taxed twice on the dividend it receives from a subsidiary?",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "No - Section 80M of the Income-tax Act provides a deduction on inter-corporate dividends to a holding company when the dividend is further distributed to its shareholders at least one month before the return-filing due date. The deduction is capped at the amount of dividend so distributed. Section 80M is available even where the holding company has elected Section 115BAA - it is one of the two carve-outs alongside Section 80JJAA. This effectively eliminates economic double taxation across the parent-subsidiary chain."
              }
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "name": "Can a Gurugram holding company elect the 22 percent rate under Section 115BAA?",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "Yes. Any domestic company - including a holding company - can elect Section 115BAA by filing Form 10-IC and accept a 22 percent base rate (effective approximately 25.17 percent after surcharge and cess). The election is once and for all - cannot be reversed. The trade-off is that most Chapter VI-A deductions are lost, but Sections 80JJAA (employment generation) and 80M (inter-corporate dividend) remain available. Model the dividend cadence before electing - 115BAA at the wrong layer can block the Section 80M chain in years where the holding does not redistribute on time."
              }
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "name": "What is the limit on a loan from a holding company to its SPV?",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "Section 186 of the Companies Act, 2013 caps total inter-corporate loans and investments at the higher of 60 percent of paid-up capital plus free reserves plus securities premium, OR 100 percent of free reserves plus securities premium. Any amount above this cap requires a special resolution under Section 186(3) with MGT-14 filing. Contravention attracts a fine of INR 25,000 to INR 5,00,000 on the company and INR 25,000 to INR 1,00,000 on every officer in default."
              }
            },
