              "@type": "Question",
              "name": "Do I need SEBI registration for an SPV under an AIF?",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "The SPV itself does not separately register with SEBI. The Alternative Investment Fund (AIF) registers under the SEBI (Alternative Investment Funds) Regulations, 2012 as Category I, II, or III. The AIF can then invest into a downstream investee SPV without further SEBI registration of the SPV. The SPV must, however, comply with the FDI route conditions if the AIF takes foreign capital, and must report to SEBI through the AIF on a quarterly basis under Regulation 28 of the AIF Regulations."
              }
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "name": "Can a foreign investor own 100 percent of an Indian SPV?",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "Yes in most sectors under the automatic route of the FDI policy. Some sectors have caps - defence (74 percent automatic), insurance (74 percent), media (different per sub-sector), and prohibited sectors (lottery, gambling, tobacco, atomic energy, railway operations). Press Note 3 of April 2020 makes FDI from any country sharing a land border with India subject to government approval through the DPIIT route, with timelines of 8 to 18 weeks. The SPV must report the allotment via Form FC-GPR within 30 days under FEMA 20(R) Rule 4(3) via the FIRMS portal through the AD bank, file Form FLA annually by 15 July."
              }
            },
