<section class="content-section" id="what-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">What Is an SPV and a Holding Company</h2>
                <div class="content-text what-is-definition">
                    
                    
<p><strong>A Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV) is a ring-fenced subsidiary incorporated for a specific project, asset, or financing objective whose Memorandum of Association is drafted with a narrow object clause. A holding company is the parent entity defined under Section 2(46) of the Companies Act, 2013 that holds another company as its subsidiary under the Section 2(87) tests of more than 50 percent share capital or control over Board composition.</strong></p>
<p>The SPV is bankruptcy-remote - its creditors cannot pursue the parent and the parent cannot pull SPV assets back without following Section 188 related-party-transaction discipline. The holding company sits at the top, consolidates accounts under Section 129(3), and uses Section 80M to wash inter-corporate dividends. Common use cases: real estate land bank per project, AIF investee SPV, family office multi-asset consolidation, joint venture vehicle, IP holding for licensing royalties, foreign-investor India entry vehicle.</p>
<p>The regulatory architecture spans five statutes. The <a href="https://www.mca.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Companies Act, 2013</a> sets the entity vehicle (Section 7 incorporation), the parent-subsidiary tests (Section 2(46) holding, Section 2(87) subsidiary), the consolidation duty (Section 129(3) read with Rule 6 Companies (Accounts) Rules 2014), the inter-corporate loan and investment caps (Section 186 - higher of 60 percent of paid-up plus free reserves OR 100 percent of free reserves), and the related-party-transaction discipline (Section 188). The <a href="https://www.incometax.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Income-tax Act</a> read with the Income-tax Act 2025 (effective AY 2026-27) sets Section 80M inter-corporate dividend deduction (the only Chapter VI-A item, alongside Section 80JJAA, surviving a Section 115BAA election), Section 115BAA 22 percent concessional rate via Form 10-IC (effective approx 25.17 percent after surcharge and cess), Section 56(2)(viib) premium-on-issue check, Section 92 to 92F transfer pricing, and Section 248(2) voluntary strike-off route via Form STK-2. SEBI regulations cover SPV usage in pooled vehicles - <a href="https://www.sebi.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SEBI (Alternative Investment Funds) Regulations, 2012</a> for Category I, II, III AIF investee SPVs; SEBI (Real Estate Investment Trusts) Regulations, 2014 and SEBI (Infrastructure Investment Trusts) Regulations, 2014 for asset-class holding SPVs. FEMA (Non-Debt Instruments) Rules, 2019 and FEMA (Overseas Investment) Rules, 2022 govern inbound (Form FC-GPR within 30 days of allotment under FEMA 20(R) Rule 4(3)) and outbound (Form ODI through AD bank) SPV structures, with Press Note 3 of April 2020 routing investments from any country sharing a land border with India through government approval (8 to 18 week timeline).</p>
<p>The architectural decision behind an SPV-plus-holding is not a Companies Act formality. The MoA object clause determines whether a lender treats the SPV as bankruptcy-remote at default. The Section 115BAA election at the wrong layer can block the Section 80M dividend chain in years where the holding does not redistribute on time. The Section 186 cap can block the next inter-corporate loan if not pre-cleared with a special resolution. The FDI route (automatic vs approval) determines whether the foreign parent enters India in 10 days or 18 weeks. The shareholder agreement determines whether the Series-B investor accepts the SPV without a holdco haircut.</p>
<p>Patron's role spans the full structure design and implementation - scoping workshop with founder, family principal, fund manager, or foreign principal to map the business objective (ring-fence, raise, exit, tax, FEMA gate), shortlist 2 to 3 structure options with quantified tax and FEMA outcomes, freeze the chosen architecture in a one-page structure diagram, file SPICe+ Part A name reservation for both holding and SPV, draft an investment-holding main-object clause for the parent and a narrow main-object clause for the SPV (this is what makes the SPV bankruptcy-remote), file SPICe+ Part B with AGILE-PRO-S, e-MoA, e-AoA, INC-9 returning CoI, PAN, TAN, EPFO, ESIC for each entity in one cycle, design the share class architecture (equity, CCPS, CCDs, preference), prepare the shareholder agreement with anti-dilution, drag-along, tag-along, ROFR, ROFO, and reserved-matter clauses that survive future investor diligence, model the inter-corporate dividend chain and Section 80M sequencing, file Form 10-IC for Section 115BAA election where favourable, structure FDI inbound (automatic or approval) with Form FC-GPR through FIRMS portal under FEMA 20(R), structure outbound investment with Form ODI under FEMA (Overseas Investment) Rules 2022, set up Section 186 board and special resolution for inter-corporate loans beyond statutory cap, and activate the 12-month rolling compliance calendar (Section 129(3) consolidated accounts, Form AOC-1 attachment to AOC-4, Form MGT-7 annual return, Form DPT-3 annual loan return by 30 June, Form 3CEB transfer pricing under Section 92E by 31 October, Form FLA annual by 15 July, and ITR-6 by 31 October). Starting INR 24,999 (Exl GST and Govt. Charges).</p>


                </div>
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
                    <p><strong>Key Terms for SPV and Holding Setup:</strong></p>
                    
<div class="key-term"><strong>Holding Company:</strong> Defined under Section 2(46) of the Companies Act, 2013 as a company that holds another company as its subsidiary, where subsidiary is determined under the Section 2(87) tests.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Subsidiary Company:</strong> A company in which the holding company controls the composition of the Board, OR exercises or controls more than 50 percent of the total voting power, OR is a subsidiary of a subsidiary - per Section 2(87) of the Companies Act, 2013.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Wholly Owned Subsidiary (WOS):</strong> A subsidiary where the holding company owns 100 percent of the share capital; the most common SPV form for clean ring-fencing.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV):</strong> A subsidiary incorporated for a specific project, asset, or financing objective with a narrow main-object clause in the MoA; bankruptcy-remote from the parent.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Narrow Object Clause:</strong> The MoA main-object clause restricting an SPV to a single project, asset class, or transaction; drafted to provide creditor comfort and bankruptcy-remote standing.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Inter-Corporate Dividend:</strong> Dividend paid by one domestic company to another, eligible for deduction under Section 80M of the Income-tax Act when the recipient further distributes one month before its return-filing due date.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 80M Deduction:</strong> Deduction on inter-corporate dividends to a holding company; capped at the amount of dividend further distributed; available even where the holding has elected Section 115BAA - one of two carve-outs alongside Section 80JJAA.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 115BAA Election:</strong> Optional 22 percent concessional corporate tax rate (effective approx 25.17 percent after surcharge and cess) via Form 10-IC; once-and-for-all election; cannot claim Chapter VI-A deductions other than Section 80M and Section 80JJAA.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 186 Inter-Corporate Cap:</strong> Total loans and investments by a company capped at the higher of 60 percent of paid-up plus free reserves plus securities premium, OR 100 percent of free reserves plus securities premium; above cap requires special resolution under Section 186(3).</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 188 Related-Party Transaction:</strong> Discipline for transactions between holding and subsidiary; requires Board approval, ordinary resolution where prescribed thresholds breached, and disclosure in Board's Report.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 129(3) Consolidation:</strong> Holding company must prepare consolidated financial statements covering every subsidiary, associate and joint venture; Form AOC-1 attached to AOC-4.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 56(2)(viib):</strong> Premium-on-issue check - premium above fair market value is taxed as income; valuation under Rule 11UA pre-empts the risk for shares issued to residents.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Form 10-IC:</strong> Section 115BAA election form filed with the return; once-and-for-all election cannot be reversed.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Form FC-GPR:</strong> Inbound allotment reporting form filed within 30 days of allotment to a non-resident under FEMA 20(R) Rule 4(3) via the FIRMS portal of RBI through the AD bank.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Form ODI:</strong> Outbound investment reporting form for Indian entities investing overseas under the FEMA (Overseas Investment) Rules, 2022.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Form DPT-3:</strong> Annual loan and deposit return due by 30 June each year under Rule 16 of the Companies (Acceptance of Deposits) Rules, 2014.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Form AOC-1:</strong> Statement containing salient features of financials of subsidiaries, associates, and joint ventures; attached to Form AOC-4 under Section 129(3).</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Press Note 3 of April 2020:</strong> Issued by Department for Promotion of Industry and Internal Trade routing FDI from any country sharing a land border with India through government approval; timeline 8 to 18 weeks.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>AIF SPV:</strong> Investee SPV downstream of a SEBI-registered Alternative Investment Fund under SEBI (AIF) Regulations, 2012; does not separately register with SEBI but reports through the AIF under Regulation 28.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>REIT and InvIT SPV:</strong> SPVs holding real estate or infrastructure assets under SEBI (REIT) Regulations, 2014 and SEBI (InvIT) Regulations, 2014 respectively.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Section 248(2) Voluntary Strike-Off:</strong> Route via Form STK-2 to wind up an SPV after the project closes and liabilities are settled; requires holding-company shareholder consent.</div>
<div class="key-term"><strong>Bankruptcy-Remote:</strong> Legal standing such that the SPV's creditors cannot pursue the parent and the parent cannot pull SPV assets back without Section 188 discipline; achieved through narrow MoA, separate bank accounts, separate books, and no commingling of assets.</div>


                </div>
            </div>
