<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        
<tr><td>Section 186 limit blocks the next inter-corporate loan</td><td>Founders routinely move money from holding to SPV as a loan without checking the Section 186 ceiling. Patron computes the 60 percent / 100 percent cap, prepares the Board resolution, and pre-clears the special-resolution route under Section 186(3) where the loan is larger - avoiding the INR 25,000 to INR 5,00,000 company fine plus INR 25,000 to INR 1,00,000 officer-in-default fine.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Wide MoA object clause defeats SPV ring-fencing</td><td>A boilerplate "any lawful business" object clause turns the SPV into a regular operating company and a lender ignores the ring-fence at default. Patron drafts a NARROW main-object clause keyed to the specific project, asset, or transaction - and stands behind that drafting at lender diligence and on creditor enforcement.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Section 115BAA election done at the wrong layer</td><td>Electing 115BAA at the holding company can block the Section 80M chain in years where the holding does not redistribute on time. Patron models the dividend cadence first across the next 36 months and elects 115BAA only at the layer where the chain breaks - not by default at every layer.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Press Note 3 country-of-concern blocks the foreign parent</td><td>Investors from countries sharing a land border with India fall under the Press Note 3 (April 2020) approval route. Patron pre-clears the FDI route, prepares the DPIIT application, and signals realistic timelines (8 to 18 weeks) so the deal does not rely on an automatic-route assumption that fails diligence.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Section 80M cadence missed forfeits the deduction</td><td>Section 80M requires the holding to redistribute one month before its own return-filing due date. Patron diaries the dividend cadence and sequences the holding-to-shareholder dividend declaration before the cutoff to lock the deduction every year.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Section 56(2)(viib) premium-on-issue triggers tax</td><td>Premium above fair market value is taxed as income at the SPV; valuation under Rule 11UA pre-empts the risk. Patron commissions a DCF or NAV valuation aligned with the subscription price before allotment.</td></tr>
<tr><td>FC-GPR missed within 30-day FEMA 20(R) window</td><td>Missing the 30-day FC-GPR window converts a clean inbound into an RBI compounding application that can take 6 to 12 months and attract compounding fees. Patron diaries the allotment date and files FC-GPR on day 10 to day 15 through the FIRMS portal via the AD bank.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Section 188 related-party transaction discipline missed</td><td>Inter-corporate transactions between holding and subsidiary need Board approval, ordinary resolution at prescribed thresholds, and Board Report disclosure. Patron sets up the related-party transaction calendar and the Form AOC-2 disclosure template.</td></tr>


                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

