<!-- FAQ SECTION -->
<section id="faq-section" class="content-section" style="background-color: #ffffff;">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <div class="faq-expanded">
                <aside class="faq-expanded__aside">
                    <h2 class="faq-expanded__title">FAQs: Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV) and Holding Company Setup in Gurugram</h2>
                    <p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV) and Holding Company Setup for Gurugram businesses, answered by our CA and CS team.</p>
                    @include('partials.faq-enquiry-form', ['enquiryLocation' => 'Gurugram', 'enquiryService' => 'Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV) and Holding Company Setup in Gurugram'])
                </aside>
                <div class="faq-expanded__list">
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Is SPV legal in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Yes. Special Purpose Vehicles are entirely legal under Indian corporate, securities, tax and regulatory frameworks. SPVs are not a separate legal category - they are structures created using existing entity forms (Private Limited or Public Limited Company under the Companies Act 2013, LLP under the LLP Act 2008, Trust under the Indian Trusts Act 1882). The Companies Act permits any company to define a limited objects clause restricting the entity to a specific project or transaction - that company effectively functions as an SPV. Government entities under Smart Cities Mission, NHAI HAM, REITs, InvITs and ARCs are all SPV structures.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the difference between SPV and holding company?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>An SPV is an entity for a specific limited purpose - one project, one asset, one transaction. A holding company under Section 2(46) of the Companies Act 2013 is a company that has at least one subsidiary - it is the parent in a multi-entity group. An SPV is typically a subsidiary or a project entity, often owned by a holding company. A holding company is broader - it is the consolidation point. A holding company can hold multiple SPVs as part of its group structure.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How is a holding company defined under Section 2(46) of the Companies Act?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Section 2(46) defines a holding company as a company of which another company is a subsidiary. The complementary Section 2(87) defines a subsidiary as a company in which the holding company either (a) controls the composition of the Board of Directors, OR (b) exercises or controls more than one-half of the total voting power. Either limb is sufficient - economic ownership alone does not create a subsidiary if voting power or board control is not present. Differential voting rights and board-control arrangements need to be modelled carefully.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Is the transfer between holding and 100% subsidiary tax-exempt?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Yes, under Section 47(iv) and 47(v) of the Income-tax Act 1961, transfer of a capital asset by an Indian holding company to its 100% Wholly Owned Subsidiary (where the WoS is an Indian company), and the reverse transfer from WoS to holding company, are exempt from capital gains tax. The exemption is subject to Section 47A clawback - if the WoS status is broken within 8 years of the transfer, or if the transferred capital asset is converted to stock-in-trade, the exemption is reversed and capital gains tax applies retrospectively to the year of transfer.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the role of SPVs in REITs and InvITs?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Under SEBI (Real Estate Investment Trusts) Regulations 2014 and SEBI (Infrastructure Investment Trusts) Regulations 2014, the REIT or InvIT (which is a Trust under the Indian Trusts Act 1882) holds asset SPVs that own the underlying real estate or infrastructure assets. The trust must hold more than 50% of the SPV. Income from the underlying assets flows through the SPVs to the trust and then to unit-holders. The SPV-trust structure enables clean asset ring-fencing, simplified listing and tax-efficient pass-through income. Listed examples include Embassy REIT, Mindspace, IRB InvIT and IndiGrid.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Can SPVs be used by family offices in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Yes, and they are increasingly common. Family offices use a holding company at the top with multiple operating-business subsidiaries and investment SPVs. The holding-subsidiary structure unlocks Section 80M dividend cascade (one-tier tax), Section 47 intra-group capital gains exemption on asset moves, Section 129 Consolidated Financial Statements for clean external view, and clean succession planning through holding company share transfers rather than asset-level transfers. Patron has structured several family office groups with 4 to 12 underlying entities under a single Pvt Ltd holding.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is Section 79 of the Income-tax Act for SPV or holding loss carry-forward?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Section 79 of the Income-tax Act 1961 governs carry-forward of business losses in closely-held companies (other than start-ups recognised under Section 79(2)). It requires that at least 51% of the voting power on the last day of the year in which the loss was incurred continues to be beneficially held on the last day of the year in which set-off is sought. Funding rounds, secondary sales and ownership changes that drop continuity below 51% break the carry-forward. SPVs intended to absorb losses (loss-utilising vehicles) must factor Section 79 carefully - Patron's structuring memo models this at the start.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Does an SPV need FDI approval if foreign-funded?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Foreign Direct Investment in an Indian SPV follows the standard FDI policy under the FEMA Non-Debt Instruments Rules 2019. Most sectors allow 100% FDI under the automatic route. Sensitive sectors (defence, broadcasting, retail with multi-brand restrictions, telecom in some cases) need government approval. Press Note 3 of 2020 mandates government approval where any beneficial owner is from a land-bordering country (China, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, Nepal, Myanmar, Afghanistan). Form FC-GPR must be filed within 30 days of share allotment. Patron handles the FEMA filings as part of the structuring engagement.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Quick Answers -->
            <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:32px;">
                <p><strong>Quick Answers</strong></p>
                
<dl class="quick-answers" style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(260px,1fr));gap:16px;">
  <div><dt style="font-weight:700;color:var(--blue);">Minimum capital for a Pvt Ltd holding or SPV?</dt><dd>None - the Companies (Amendment) Act, 2015 removed the INR 1 lakh minimum.</dd></div>
  <div><dt style="font-weight:700;color:var(--blue);">Can an LLP be a holding company?</dt><dd>Yes - but it cannot elect Section 115BAA and Section 80M does not apply on the LLP side.</dd></div>
  <div><dt style="font-weight:700;color:var(--blue);">Consolidated FS required?</dt><dd>Yes - Section 129(3) Companies Act, 2013 read with Rule 6 Companies (Accounts) Rules, 2014. Form AOC-1 attached to AOC-4.</dd></div>
  <div><dt style="font-weight:700;color:var(--blue);">Section 56(2)(viib) premium risk?</dt><dd>Premium above fair market value taxed as income; Rule 11UA valuation pre-empts the risk.</dd></div>
  <div><dt style="font-weight:700;color:var(--blue);">SPV strike-off after project closes?</dt><dd>Section 248(2) voluntary strike-off via Form STK-2 after settling liabilities and obtaining holding-company shareholder consent.</dd></div>
  <div><dt style="font-weight:700;color:var(--blue);">Section 186 cap?</dt><dd>Higher of 60 percent of paid-up + free reserves + securities premium OR 100 percent of free reserves + securities premium; above requires special resolution.</dd></div>
  <div><dt style="font-weight:700;color:var(--blue);">FC-GPR window?</dt><dd>Within 30 days of allotment under FEMA 20(R) Rule 4(3) via FIRMS portal.</dd></div>
  <div><dt style="font-weight:700;color:var(--blue);">Press Note 3 timeline?</dt><dd>8 to 18 weeks via DPIIT for FDI from country-of-concern parents.</dd></div>
  <div><dt style="font-weight:700;color:var(--blue);">Section 80M deduction available under 115BAA?</dt><dd>Yes - one of two carve-outs alongside Section 80JJAA.</dd></div>
  <div><dt style="font-weight:700;color:var(--blue);">Patron fee?</dt><dd>Starting INR 24,999 (Exl GST and Govt. Charges).</dd></div>
</dl>


