<section class="content-section" style="background: var(--orange-lighter) !important; border-left: 4px solid var(--orange);">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Three Time-Sensitive Triggers for SPV and Holding Structures</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                Three time-sensitive triggers anchor every SPV-and-holding engagement. Form FC-GPR is due within 30 days of allotment to a non-resident under FEMA 20(R) Rule 4(3) - missing it converts a clean inbound into an RBI compounding application that can take 6 to 12 months. Form 10-IC for Section 115BAA election must be filed by the return-filing due date for the year the rate is first claimed - missing it locks the company at the 30 percent rate for the entire year and forfeits the once-and-for-all 22 percent base (effective approx 25.17 percent including surcharge and cess). DPT-3 annual loan return is due by 30 June each year covering the previous financial year and is the inter-corporate loan disclosure that RBI and ROC cross-check - default attracts Section 450 fine of up to INR 10,000 plus INR 1,000 per day continuing. Beyond these, the Section 80M chain requires the holding company to redistribute dividends one month before its own return-filing due date - missing the cadence forfeits the deduction for that year and creates economic double taxation across the parent-subsidiary chain. Section 186 inter-corporate loan and investment caps must be cleared before transferring funds from holding to SPV (or vice versa); breach attracts INR 25,000 to INR 5,00,000 company fine plus INR 25,000 to INR 1,00,000 officer-in-default fine.

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

